// Package smt provides utilities for exporting gnark constraint systems to SMT solver formats.
//
// This package enables formal verification of gnark circuits by extracting the actual
// PlonK constraints generated by the gnark compiler and exporting them in formats
// compatible with SMT solvers like cvc5.
//
// # Motivation
//
// Existing SMT verification tests (e.g., in std/rangecheck/smt_verify/) manually encode
// constraint logic in C++. While useful, these tests don't verify the actual constraints
// produced by the gnark compiler - they verify hand-written approximations.
//
// This package bridges that gap by:
//   - Parsing compiled gnark constraint systems (SCS/PlonK format)
//   - Extracting actual qL, qR, qO, qM, qC coefficients from constraints
//   - Exporting to cvc5-compatible C++ or SMT-LIB2 format
//
// # Usage
//
// Basic usage to compile a circuit and export constraints:
//
//	circuit := &MyCircuit{}
//	opts := smt.DefaultCompileOptions()
//	opts.TestName = "MyCircuit"
//
//	result, err := smt.CompileCircuit(circuit, opts)
//	if err != nil {
//	    log.Fatal(err)
//	}
//
//	// Print summary
//	result.PrintSummary()
//	result.PrintConstraints()
//
//	// Write to file
//	result.WriteToFile("verify_mycircuit.cpp")
//
// # Export Formats
//
// The package supports two export formats:
//
// ## C++ (cvc5 API)
//
// Generates standalone C++ code that uses the cvc5 C++ API to verify constraints.
// Includes helper functions, constraint data as vectors, and test scaffolding.
//
// ## SMT-LIB2
//
// Generates standard SMT-LIB2 format using finite field theory (QF_FF logic).
// Can be used with any SMT solver supporting finite field reasoning.
//
// # Constraint Format
//
// PlonK constraints have the form:
//
//	qL*xa + qR*xb + qO*xc + qM*(xa*xb) + qC = 0
//
// Where:
//   - xa, xb, xc are wire (variable) indices
//   - qL, qR, qO are linear coefficients
//   - qM is the multiplication coefficient
//   - qC is the constant coefficient
//
// # Example: Verifying Range Check Constraints
//
// See std/rangecheck/smt_verify/generate_test.go for a complete example that:
//   - Compiles a range check circuit
//   - Exports the actual PlonK constraints
//   - Generates C++ verification code
//
// # Integration with cvc5
//
// The generated C++ code requires cvc5 to be installed. Build with:
//
//	g++ -std=c++17 -I/path/to/cvc5/include verify_test.cpp -lcvc5 -o verify_test
//
// Or use static linking as shown in the Makefile examples.
package smt
